  "prompt": "How gear ratio varies power?",
  "response": "Gear ratio affects power transmission in several key ways:\n\n1. Torque Multiplication\n- Higher gear ratios increase torque output\n- Lower gear ratios reduce torque but increase speed\n- Torque = Input torque \u00d7 Gear ratio\n\n2. Speed Relationship\n- Inverse relationship between gear ratio and rotational speed\n- Higher ratio = Lower output speed\n- Lower ratio = Higher output speed\n\n3. Power Transfer Principles\n- Power remains relatively constant through gear system\n- Power = Torque \u00d7 Angular velocity\n- Efficiency slightly reduces power due to friction losses\n\n4. Mechanical Advantage\n- Larger gear ratios provide mechanical advantage\n- More force can be applied with lower input effort\n- Useful in applications requiring high torque\n\n5. Performance Characteristics\n- Low gear ratios: High-speed, low-torque scenarios\n- High gear ratios: Low-speed, high-torque applications\n\n6. Common Examples\n- Vehicles: Different gear ratios for acceleration and cruising\n- Industrial machinery: Adaptable power transmission\n- Robotics: Precision movement control\n\n7. Efficiency Considerations\n- Gear ratio affects overall mechanical efficiency\n- More complex gear trains have increased friction losses\n\nUnderstanding these principles helps optimize power transmission in mechanical systems.",
